<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=16491&amp;p=204654#p204654</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=16491&amp;p=204654#p204654"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Video -- How Toy Story's 3D was programmed]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=16491&amp;p=204654#p204654"><![CDATA[
The Genesis uses packed pixels, where a byte represents two pixels side by side. Most S-PPU background modes, on the other hand, use planar pixels. A 2-pixel column is 2 bits out of each of 2, 4, or 8 bytes. The packed mode on the S-PPU is mode 7, and pixel doubling using the scaling feature would work better than trying to actually write a pair of distinct pixels.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Sep 16, 2017 9:37 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
